Examining Patterns in Voting and Wellbeing in the United States¶

When complaining about how much life sucks on any social media platform, a common sentiment relayed to the complainer is to "vote more!" Especially around election time. That got us thinking.

We decided to study whether voting percentages were correlated in any way to quality of life. However, eventually we also started wondering if said voting percentages were more dependent on who voted rather than where they vote. Thus, we decided to investigate these questions by exmaining at voting, demographic, and wellbeing data United States states, to see if there were any insights to be discovered!

Data Collection & Curation¶

To start, we will need to find a dataset that can describe some characteristics pertaining to quality of life per state. When searching, we came across some datasets by WalletHub which assigned scores for each of the 50 states on characteristics like happiness, livability, stress, wealth gap between races, and quality of healthcare. They calculated these scores by comparing states across key dimensions and evaluating the states based on a number of metrics pertaining to the dimension. For example, for the 'Livability Score,' researchers examined metrics relating to five key dimensions: Affordability, Economy, Education & Health, Quality of Life, and Safety. Some metrics used to evaluate the Affordability dimension, would thereby include Cost of Living, Median Annual Household Income, Homeownership Rate, and more.

To further clarify, happiness scores describe general life satisfaction and wellness, livability scores describe the best states to live in, stress scores describe general level of stress in each state, wealth gap scores describe economic racial inequality, and healthcare scores describe the quality of healthcare in each state. Their methodology appears to be very thorough, and if we assume their assigned scores are truly reflective of a characteristic of wellbeing/quality of life, we could examine these in relation to voting data!

Thus, to start, we scraped the data for happiness, livability, stress, wealth gap between races, and quality of healthcare using the BeautifulSoup library.

happy_soup = BeautifulSoup(happiness_page.content, "html")

livability_page = requests.get('https://wallethub.com/edu/best-states-to-live-in/62617', headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'})
life_soup = BeautifulSoup(livability_page.content, "html")

stress_page = requests.get('https://wallethub.com/edu/most-stressful-states/32218', headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'})
stress_soup = BeautifulSoup(stress_page.content, "html")

wealth_gap_page = requests.get('https://wallethub.com/edu/states-with-the-highest-and-lowest-financial-gaps-by-race/9842', headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'})
wealth_gap_soup = BeautifulSoup(wealth_gap_page.content, "html")

healthcare_page = requests.get('https://wallethub.com/edu/states-with-best-health-care/23457', headers={'User-Agent':'Mozilla/5.0'})
healthcare_soup = BeautifulSoup(healthcare_page.content, "html")

wealth_gap_matches = wealth_gap_soup.findAll('table')[0].findAll('tr')[1:]
healthcare_matches = healthcare_soup.findAll('table')[0].findAll('tr')[1:]

for i in range(0, 50):
    happiness_rows = happiness_matches[i].findAll('td')
    happiness_states.append(happiness_rows[1].text)
    happiness_scores.append(float(happiness_rows[2].text))
    
    livability_rows = livability_matches[i].findAll('td')
    livability_states.append(livability_rows[1].text)
    livability_scores.append(float(livability_rows[2].text))

    stress_rows = stress_matches[i].findAll('td')
    stress_states.append(stress_rows[1].text)
    stress_scores.append(float(stress_rows[2].text))

for i in range(0, 51): #these include DC!
    wealth_gap_rows = wealth_gap_matches[i].findAll('td')
    wealth_gap_states.append(wealth_gap_rows[1].text)
    wealth_gap_scores.append(float(wealth_gap_rows[2].text))

    healthcare_rows = healthcare_matches[i].findAll('td')
    healthcare_states.append(healthcare_rows[1].text)
    healthcare_scores.append(float(healthcare_rows[2].text))

state_happiness = {'state': happiness_states, 'happiness_score': happiness_scores} 
state_livability = {'state': livability_states, 'livability_score': livability_scores} 
state_stress = {'state': stress_states, 'stress_score': stress_scores} 
state_wealth_gap = {'state': wealth_gap_states, 'wealth_gap_score': wealth_gap_scores} 
state_healthcare = {'state': healthcare_states, 'healthcare_score': healthcare_scores} 

state_happiness = pd.DataFrame(state_happiness)
state_livability = pd.DataFrame(state_livability)
state_stress = pd.DataFrame(state_stress)
state_wealth_gap = pd.DataFrame(state_wealth_gap)
state_healthcare = pd.DataFrame(state_healthcare)

wellbeing_scores = pd.merge(state_happiness, state_livability,  how='left', on=['state'])
wellbeing_scores = pd.merge(wellbeing_scores, state_stress, how='left', on=['state'])
wellbeing_scores = pd.merge(wellbeing_scores, state_wealth_gap, how='left', on=['state'])
wellbeing_scores = pd.merge(wellbeing_scores, state_healthcare, how='left', on=['state'])

wellbeing_scores.sort_values('state', inplace=True)
wellbeing_scores.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
wellbeing_scores.head(5)

Perfect! As seen above, we have the scores for each of these "wellbeing" characteistics. Now, we need to pull in some voting data. We were able to find a 2018 dataset from the Census which provides voting data information. It also includes details about voter gender and race that may come in handy later, but for now, let us focus on getting just the total registration and voting data.

Upon reading in the dataset, we need to clean it up. First, this census data is a dataset with a multiindex (state and demographic) which can make things tricky. If we want to work with both the wellbeing dataset and census dataset, then we need to rename the states such that we can merge the datasets on state name later. Here, we rename the multiindex names, and the names of the state for ease of use. We also drop DC since it doesn't appear consistently in the wellbeing data.

There are some columns that we do not need. For example, 'Margin of Error' columns are not neccessary to our project as we won't be using them. We also don't need any of the Citizen categories, because we will be looking at total voting data. Furthermore, since the column catagories 'population', 'registered', and 'voted' will then have only two columns, we will drop that level as well.

We noted that some values were '-' or 'B' instead of a number. Upon further research, we found that '-' means the number is 0 or rounds to 0, and 'B' means the base is less than 75,000 and therefore too small to show the derived measure. We decided to keep these measures for now, because they provide nuance to the data beyond reassigning the data values to NaN or 0.

This table looks a lot more relevant to our open question because it is showing only the registration and voting data. We may want to examine race and demographic data later, but as our aim is to examine wellbeing characteristics in relation to voting percentages, they are currently not necessary. Similarily, perhaps we can work with population data in the future, but as for now, it doesn't appear to be particularily relevant to voting data in general. If anything, working with pure numerical data like population data may not be the right choice for a question like this, since we want to examine across states in the US. Since states can have drastically varying populations, working with percentages is a safer bet.

Furthermore, though we decided to initially use total percentage of citizens who have voted, after some thought, we have decided to look at the proportion of registered citizens who have voted. We made this decision because, first, a person cannot vote until they have registered to vote. And second, once a person is registered, it is a question of whether they vote or not. Thus, this metric will be more representative of actual voting activity. Lastly, including a column with state abbreviations may come handy later so it would be good to include that.

Thus, we will create our final voting_percentage dataset with these features.

states = []
abbreviations = []
percentage_registered = []
percentage_voted = []
diff_percentage_reg_voted = []
prop_percentage_voted = []

for state, new_df in census_voting_data.groupby(level=0):
    states.append(state) #state
    abbreviations.append(state_abbreviations[state]) #state abbreviations
    percentage_registered.append(float(new_df.iloc[0, 2])) #percentage of people who are registered
    percentage_voted.append(float(new_df.iloc[0, 4])) #percentage of people who voted
    prop_percentage_voted.append(float(new_df.iloc[0, 4])/float(new_df.iloc[0, 2]) *100) #calculation proportion of reg voters
    
voting_percentages = pd.DataFrame({'state': states,
                   'abbreviation': abbreviations,
                   'percent_registered': percentage_registered,
                   'percent_voted': percentage_voted,
                   'proportion_registered_who_voted': prop_percentage_voted}, index=abbreviations)

voting_percentages.head(10)

Data Representation ~ Voting Percentages & Wellbeing Scores¶

Before studying any possible correlations in the data, we decided to study the data so we can see what we are working with. This can be difficult to do with a lot of tabular data at once; it would be good to visualize the data in full so we can see what we are working with! Thus, we decided to first create some plots which visually represented the data in each state.

Below, we created a bar chart which plots two bars per state. The bar in blue describes the percentage of citizens who are registered to vote, and the bar in orange describes the percentage of citizens who have voted. To make the plot cleaner, we opted to use abbreviations to denote the states instead of their names. Consistently, we see that the percentage of citizens registered is greater than the percentage of citizens who have voted. This, of course, makes sense since one must be registered to vote. We also see that the percentage of citizens registered to vote seems to be between a little above 50% to around 75%. The percentage of citizens who have voted appears to be between 40% and 70%. Some states also have noticebly bigger gaps than others, with Louisiana versus Hawaii being a prime example.

Morever, since we are mainly examining proportion of registered citizens who have voters, we decided to create a scatter plot, so that we can see if there are any interesting patterns amongst the proportions. Truthfully, not much can be gained from this scatterplot. We do see that the proportions seem to range between 65% and 90%. However, this proportion data without any metric to contrast it against, is not very useful. Perhaps, analyzing this proportion in tandem with other wllbeing characteristics would provide greater insight.

Next, let us visualize the wellbeing data. Though the bar graph we created above does describe the reistration and voting data for each state well, it is also pretty cramped because it has to accomodate all fifty states. This means that it would not be sensible to create another bar graph where each state has a bar denoting wellbeing index, because the bar chart would be extremely difficult to read. Furthermore, upon pondering what visual representation would be best to use, we realized that there may be patterns to be found based on the geographic location of the states. For example, could New England states consistently have high healthcare scores? If so, could we investigate whether New England states vote similarily?

With this thought in mind, we decided to create maps of the United States with the Folium and Geopandas libraries. In order to do so, we found a Geojson file online which contains the locations of each of the states. Then, for each state, we provided the voting percentage and the score of the specific wellbeing characteristic. As we mentioned before, it would not be good practice to visualize of the wellbeing data in the same plot, so we will be creating a new map for every characteristic.

In [33]:
geojson = gpd.read_file(r'georef-united-states-of-america-state-millesime.geojson')
geojson=geojson[['ste_name','geometry']] #get the geojson data we need! 

# make a map of the United States
m = folium.Map(width=500, height=500, location=[48, -102], zoom_start=3)

# create the chloropleth map, by passing in voting percentages and happiness score. 
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=r'georef-united-states-of-america-state-millesime.geojson',
    name="choropleth",
    data=voting_with_wellbeing_scores,
    columns=["state", "happiness_score"],
    key_on="feature.properties.ste_name", #bind geojson data to state name 
    fill_color="YlGn",
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    legend_name="Happiness Score",
).add_to(m)
folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)

This map displays stress scores across the United States. States with high stress scores mean that their citizens live with a higher level of stress, which is a negative. In order to show this, we changed the scale so it ranged from yellow to red instead of yellow to green. It appears that the stress scores range between 32% and 61%, but there are two big clusters: one cluster of states have scores ranging from 32% to 47%, and another cluster have scores ranging from 47% to 61%. Interestingly, it apepars that these clusters are along the North-South divide in the United States, with northern states tending to have a lower stress score, and southern states tending to have a higehr stress score. It's also really interesting, because when we compare this to the livability map they appear to mirror each other! This makes sense intuitively: the better one's living situation is, the less stressed they are.

Data Analysis ~ Let us examine voting and wellbeing!¶

Now, that we have examine both the voting percentages and wellbeing data in detail, let us examine them in tandem to see if there are any intereesting patterns.

Just to provide various perspectives on this examination, we have elected to include both a bar graph and a scatterplot. The bar graph depicts the states in order, from highest wellbeing score to lowest, and presents their voting percentage data. This is one way to to see if there is any patterns related to having a higher score versus lower score.

We also decided to include the scatterplot; the scatterplot depicts the wellbeing characteristic score on the x-axis and the voting percentage on the y-axis. Note, that since we are only using data from 1 year, we cannot make any presumptive claims on causation. If there does appear to be a trend in the data, the most we will say is that it is correlated. We also decided to do fit a linear regression model on each of the scatterplots to get their coefficient and r-values.

In [40]:
voting_with_wellbeing_scores.sort_values('happiness_score', inplace=True)
voting_with_wellbeing_scores = voting_with_wellbeing_scores[::-1]
voting_with_wellbeing_scores.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

ax1 = voting_with_wellbeing_scores.plot.bar(rot=0, figsize=(20,5), x='abbreviation', y=['percent_voted'])
ax2 = voting_with_wellbeing_scores.plot.scatter(x='happiness_score', y='proportion_registered_who_voted')

ind = [[i] for i in voting_with_wellbeing_scores['happiness_score'].tolist()]
dep = voting_with_wellbeing_scores['proportion_registered_who_voted'].tolist()

lm = linear_model.LinearRegression()
lm.fit(ind, dep)
ax2.plot(ind, lm.predict(ind), color='red')
r_squared = lm.score(ind, dep)
print("R-squared value is " +str(r_squared))
print("The slope of the regression line is " +str(lm.coef_[0]))

R-squared value is 0.2919008054845902
The slope of the regression line is 0.28919076771803687

To quickly restate, we are hypothesizing that there may be a correlation between wellbeing characteristics, like happiness scores, and the proportion of registered voters.

As we described before, the two plots above display happiness scores in different ways. From the bar plot, we can see that there is higher variability in the proportion of registered citizens who have voted amongst states with higher happiness scores, while the states with lower happiness scores near the end of the bar graph seem to consistently have a percentage of 45% to 50%. Furthermore, the scatterplot was fitted with a linear regression model. The linear regression line displayed shows a possible positive trend such that the happier a state is, the more likely its citizens are to vote. The coefficient of the linear regression line is 0.29, which does not mean that the hypothesis that happiness scores and proportion of registered voters are correlated is automatically rejected, since the coefficient is not close to 0. The r-squared value, which describes how well the linear regression line fits the data, is 0.292. Since the r-squared value is low, this relationship requires further testing.

Next, we will examine whether there is a relationship between stress scores and the proportion of registered voters. From the bar plot, we can see that though there is variability in the proportion of registered citizens who have voted amongst the states, there does appear to be a slight increase in the proportion as the stress scores go down. However, it is also possible that there is not significant trend and that states like Maine, Montana, North Dakota, etc. with low stress scores and high proportions may also be outliers.

The scatterplot was again fitted with a linear regression model. The linear regression line displayed shows a slight negative trend such that the lower the stress level in a state, the more likely its citizens are to vote. Next, we will examine whether there is a relationship between wealth gap/inequality between races and the proportion of registered voters. From the bar plot, we can see that there is higher variability in the proportion of registered citizens who have voted amongst the states, so we cannot draw any meaningful conclusions from here.

Insights¶

French et al. (2014) further supports these tentative findings regarding the relationship between voting and stress scores. They found that increased cortisol levels represented increased stress, and their results noted that increased cortisol levels led to decreased probability of voting. My results agreed with their findings.

We also found some research supporting our findings regarding happiness scores. The 2019 World Happiness Report discussed how voter life satisfaction in European countries had a statistically significant relationship with cabinet vote share (Ward 2019). Even through five different models, voter well-being had a positive relationship to cabinet vote share, with p-value < 0.01 in all five cases. Our data showed a comparable trend with a positive relationship between state happiness score and the proportion of registered who voted.

Works Cited: French, J. A., Smith, K. B., Alford, J. R., Guck, A., Birnie, A. K., & Hibbing, J. R. (2014). Cortisol and politics: variance in voting behavior is predicted by baseline cortisol levels. Physiology & behavior, 133, 61-67. Accessed 16 May 2022, from https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0031938414002595. Ward, G. (2019). Happiness and voting behaviour. World Happiness Report 2019, 46-65.

Further research Paths: Data analysis could include looking at the elections themselves!¶

Perhaps it's not the quality of life but more about the election itself? (# https://www.brennancenter.org/our-work/research-reports/voting-laws-roundup-may-2021)¶

The below code is incomplete but if further worked upon, it could examine the factors related to percentage of voting beyond quality of life. The way elections are run impacts how voters percieve not just the election, but also the government institutions they are voting for. Elections can also make it less or more difficult for citizens to vote.

The two things we start to look at here are the restrictive and expansive voting laws, as well as registration deadlines. With more time, we would examine whether states with a higher ratio of expansive tor restrictive laws passed/in motion is correlated with voting percentages. Similarily, in regards to registration deadlines, we could examine if the less stringent a state's registration deadline is, the more its citizens vote.

scores = []
